properties.Title: Snow Squall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls are expected. Under the snow squall bands, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow combined with blowing snow, and snow will quickly accumulate. ### Snow squalls cause weather conditions to vary considerably; changes from clear skies to heavy snow within just a few kilometres are common. Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow squalls possible tonight into Sunday. Snow squalls are expected to develop off Lake Nipigon tonight behind a strong cold front and persist through Sunday. There is a possibility that the squalls will continue through Monday as well as winds are expected to remain out of the north or northwest. Localized accumulations of 15 to 25 cm are possible by Sunday evening with additional snowfall possible on Monday. Travel conditions along Highway 11 could be particularly hazardous. Motorists are advised to watch for quickly changing weather conditions and adjust their driving accordingly. ### Travel may be hazardous due to sudden changes in the weather. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Road closures are possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 20 cm is expected. A strong cold front will result in heavy snow over parts of southern Alberta this weekend. The most intense snow is expected tonight and through the overnight hours. General accumulations of 10 cm will occur by Sunday morning, however, some areas could see upwards of 20 cm. Temperatures are also expected to fall throughout today as the cold front passes. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A long period of snowfall with total amounts of 20 to 30 cm is expected. Snow continues to fall over northeastern BC tonight and is expected to continue well into Saturday evening. BC North Peace River - will see 25 cm of snow accumulation by midnight Saturday. BC South Peace River - can expect 25 to 30 cm of snow for northern sections including Chetwynd and Dawson Creek by midnight Saturday. Southern sections will receive 10 to 15 cm total. Fort Nelson - will see 20 to 25 cm of snow over southern sections including Sikanni Chief by midnight Saturday. The community of Fort Nelson will receive lesser amounts of near 10 cm total with this system. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become difficult to navigate due to accumulating snow. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
